        <div2>
          <head>
            <title type="main">“Folly is the cloke of knavery.”</title>
          </head>
          <byline>
            <docAuthor>Morton D. <name>Paley</name></docAuthor>
          </byline>
          <p>I had always thought of this Proverb of Hell as originating in <hi rend="i">The Marriage.</hi>
However, Walter Scott in <hi rend="i">Waverley</hi>, in speaking of Davie Gellately, says: “Davie had no
mind to explain, and had wit enough to make his folly cloak his knavery. . .” (Andrew Hook, ed., Penguin,
1972 [116]). This seems too close for coincidence, and so there must either be a common source or an
intermediary source, unless we assume that Sir Walter had been conversing with Blake’s Devils. Does anybody
know?</p>
        </div2>
      </div1>
